          "body": "In the two highest-rank cases, after the fat is burned on the altar, the remainder of the bull — hide, flesh, head, legs, entrails, refuse — is taken 'outside the camp to a clean place' and burned there (vv. 12, 21). 'Outside the camp' is Leviticus's consistent designation for the place of uncleanness, quarantine, and exclusion (Lev. 13:46; 14:3; Num. 5:3). The sin-laden carcass cannot remain within the covenant community; it is expelled. It is precisely this detail that the writer of Hebrews makes the interpretive linchpin of the atonement: 'For the bodies of those animals whose blood is brought into the holy place by the high priest as an offering for sin, are burned outside the camp. Therefore Jesus also, that He might sanctify the people through His own blood, suffered *outside the gate*' (Heb. 13:11-12). The crucifixion outside Jerusalem's walls was not incidental geography — it was the deliberate fulfillment of Leviticus 4:12, 21. Jesus occupied the space the sin-bearing carcass occupied: expelled from the holy community, burned in the place of exclusion, bearing the uncleanness that cannot remain where God dwells."
